ce:section.ce:para:
To address these existing challenges, we designed a dual-photocathode array propelled paper-based ratiometric PEC analytical device (Scheme 1
                     A). The programmed dual-photocathode array was comprised of a working electrode (PCE1) and internal reference electrode (PCE2), which were responsible for producing independent working signal (Iw
                     ) and internal reference signal (Ir
                     ). For the generation of cathodic photocurrent signal, selecting high-performance p-type photoactive materials is vital. Cu2O has been employed as an attractive p-type semiconductor for PEC sensing because of its environmental friendliness, easy to fabricate, low cost, and narrow band gap (∼2.0 eV) [17,18]. In this respect, we fabricated a paper-based Cu2O with unique pyramid-shaped structure by taking full advantage of the comprehensive merits of Cu2O and interconnected paper fibers network [19]. To further realize the valid charge separation and transfer, graphene quantum dots (GQDs) and AgI nanoparticles (NPs) were selected as different sensitization units due to its befitting band potential, strong photoresponse capacity, and good charge mobility behavior [20,21]. The formed cascading polynary sensitization structure could boost the significant enhancement of photocurrent. For the formulation of signal amplification model, electron-transfer tunneling distance regulation strategy was adopted due to its simple but efficient controllability to signal response [22,23]. Structurally stable DNA nanostructure is the core component to build this type of signal regulation strategy. However, conventionally used double stranded DNA nanostructures possess poor rigidness, which leads to unsatisfactory determination accuracy and stability. Herein, a new DNA bridge nanostructure mediated electron-transfer tunneling distance regulation strategy was established by combining with the duplex specific nuclease (DSN)-induced target recycling amplification. Compared with traditional double stranded DNA nanostructure, the engineered DNA bridge nanostructure consisting of DNA duplex-based bridge pier and abutment exhibited significantly enhanced rigidity, thereby resulting in the stronger signal amplification capability and better analytical performance.
